Regarding Nightmare, from SC 1 to SC2.  Remember all those moves that were great, but once you finished the combo you had a long time vulnerable?  There's a lot more you can chain off of them now <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   I like Nightmare in the first one, but he only had so many ways of initiating attack, and it was so slow you could just parry/repel them every time.  In SC2, Nightmare is WAY more agile and versatile once he starts swinging the blade around.  Makes him a lot more interesting, and a lot harder to defend against when he goes all offensive.  Which is how Nightmare should be played <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
